AUXILIARY_DESCRIPTIONS.ten undocumented aliens: hidden in the tractor-trailer's sleeper area, discovered at the immigration checkpoint stop
AUXILIARY_DESCRIPTIONS.Zeba Williams: co-defendant of Raymond McMillon, driver of the tractor-trailer at the immigration checkpoint stop, found to have voluntarily consented to the search
AUXILIARY_DESCRIPTIONS.Ramon De La Cruz: defendant who was sentenced to 41 months' imprisonment and appealed the decision, arguing that United States Border Patrol Agent's immigration questions unlawfully extended the duration of the immigration checkpoint stop, claimed possessory interest in the tractor-trailer, had his speedy trial clock begin on July 8, 2014, filed motions to suppress and for discovery
AUXILIARY_DESCRIPTIONS.Raymond McMillon: involved in a law case, raising issues on appeal including motion to dismiss the indictment and sufficiency of evidence, made arguments regarding voluntariness of consent to search
AUXILIARY_DESCRIPTIONS.Luis Pena: United States Border Patrol Agent who approached the driver-side door of the tractor-trailer and questioned Zeba Williams and Ramon De La Cruz
AUXILIARY_DESCRIPTIONS.Manuel Hernandez: United States Border Patrol Agent who prepared to have his canine perform a sniff of the tractor-trailer's exterior steps
AUXILIARY_DESCRIPTIONS.Aroxa: canine used by Manuel Hernandez for inspection that alerted to the presence of contraband
AUXILIARY_DESCRIPTIONS.Jorge Miguel Hernandez-Gomez: alien being transported, discovered hidden in the tractor-trailer's sleeper area
AUXILIARY_DESCRIPTIONS.United States District Court: court where motions are heard and ruled upon, responsible for making ends-of-justice findings on the record, correctly concluded that less than seventy non-excludable days elapsed between Ramon De La Cruz's indictment and trial, held a hearing on Ramon De La Cruz's motions to suppress and for discovery
AUXILIARY_DESCRIPTIONS.Speedy Trial Act: federal law governing trial timing, excluding certain periods of delay, including continuances granted for ends-of-justice findings
